From Perry Metzger Subject Re Fifth Amendment and Passwords In article Germano Caronni writes Just a As a provider of a public BBS service aren't you bound by law to gurantee intelligble access to the data of the users on the BBS if police comes with sufficent authorisation I guessed this would be a basic condition for such I did run a bbs some time ago but that was in Switzerland You are obliged to let the police search the equipment if they have a proper court You are under no legal obligation to keep the data If you wish to run your BBS entirely with all data encrypted such that if the police show up they cannot read anything well thats their There are no legal restrictions on domestic use of cryptography in the United States Perry Metzger Laissez faire laissez Le monde va de lui